{"id":"2102.11690","submitter":"Pritha Dutta","authors":"Pritha Dutta, Rick Quax, Loes Crielaard and Peter M.A. Sloot","title":"Inferring temporal dynamics from cross-sectional data using Langevin\n  dynamics","comments":"17 pages, 3 figures, \"The code for the proposed method is written in\n  Mathematica programming language and is available at\n  https://github.com/Pritha17/langevin-crosssectional\"","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CE","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  Cross-sectional studies are widely prevalent since they are more feasible to\nconduct compared to longitudinal studies. However, cross-sectional data lack\nthe temporal information required to study the evolution of the underlying\nprocesses. Nevertheless, this is essential to develop predictive computational\nmodels which is the first step towards causal modelling. We propose a method\nfor inferring computational models from cross-sectional data using Langevin\ndynamics. This method can be applied to any system that can be described as\neffectively following a free energy landscape, such as protein folding, stem\ncell differentiation and reprogramming, and social systems involving human\ninteraction and social norms. A crucial assumption in our method is that the\ndata-points are gathered from a system in (local) equilibrium. The result is a\nset of stochastic differential equations which capture the temporal dynamics,\nby assuming that groups of data-points are subject to the same free energy\nlandscape and amount of noise. Our method is a 'baseline' method which\ninitiates the development of computational models which can be iteratively\nenhanced through the inclusion of expert knowledge. We validate the proposed\nmethod against two population-based longitudinal datasets and observe\nsignificant predictive power in comparison with random choice algorithms. We\nalso show how the predictive power of our 'baseline' model can b